</span><span class='line'>      <span class="nt">&lt;div</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">&quot;content&quot;</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="nt">&lt;p&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>          Much like last week, you have a number of CSS challenges before you. Follow
</span><span class='line'>          along and by the time you&#39;re done, you&#39;ll have completed your first all-css page
</span><span class='line'>          layout. (It&#39;s going to be a single-column layout, with a horizontal nav.)
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="nt">&lt;h2&gt;</span>Tasks<span class="nt">&lt;/h2&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>        <span class="nt">&lt;ol&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>          <span class="nt">&lt;li&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>            Choose a font, font-size, and color. Consider if headers should be distinct
</span><span class='line'>            from lists or body text. Set the <span class="nt">&lt;code&gt;</span>body<span class="nt">&lt;/code&gt;</span> background color to be
</span><span class='line'>            different than the <span class="nt">&lt;code&gt;</span>.wrapper<span class="nt">&lt;/code&gt;</span> div&#39;s background color.
</span><span class='line'>          <span class="nt">&lt;/li&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>          <span class="nt">&lt;li&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>            Choose an overall width (hint: set this on the wrapper div), and make the page
</span><span class='line'>            auto-center even as the browser size changes. (hint: use <span class="nt">&lt;code&gt;</span>margin: 20px
</span><span class='line'>            auto<span class="nt">&lt;/code&gt;</span> or something similar)
</span><span class='line'>          <span class="nt">&lt;/li&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>          <span class="nt">&lt;li&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>            Adjust <span class="nt">&lt;code&gt;</span>padding<span class="nt">&lt;/code&gt;</span> and <span class="nt">&lt;code&gt;</span>line-height<span class="nt">&lt;/code&gt;</span> until you&#39;re happy
</span><span class='line'>            with the general typography of your document.
</span><span class='line'>          <span class="nt">&lt;/li&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>          <span class="nt">&lt;li&gt;</span>
</span><span class='line'>            Set <span class="nt">&lt;code&gt;</span>list-style-type: none<span class="nt">&lt;/code&gt;</span> and <span class="nt">&lt;code&gt;</span>padding: 0<span class="nt">&lt;/code&gt;</span> on
</span><span class='line'>            the <span class="nt">&lt;code&gt;</span>ul<span class="nt">&lt;/code&gt;</span> element inside the <span class="nt">&lt;code&gt;</span>nav<span class="nt">&lt;/code&gt;</span> element.
